        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> Isn't it a breaking change\r\n\r\nNo, it doesn't break current behavior. It only extends the current behavior to parent directories.\r\n\r\n> that should be optional\r\n\r\nIt kind of _is_ optional, as 'exrc' defaults to false. So a user is already opting-in for loading project-local config. Furthermore, you can disable this just like any default autocmd (`:h default-autocmds`).\r\n\r\n> This behavior may surprise users \r\n\r\nI would argue that this is behavior many people would actually expect, and have definitely been frustrated in moments it didn't behave like this.\r\n\r\n> f.e. a vendor library subdirectory of some project containing an exrc file.\r\n\r\nFor this specific case, you could add the following to `.nvim.lua`:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nif vim.fn.getcwd():match(\"/vendor/\") then\r\n  return\r\nend\r\n```",
            "created_at": "2025-05-07T18:36:05Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/33889#issuecomment-2859832196",
